      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The \"marketplace of ideas\" demands that all speech, even offensive or unpopular speech, be allowed to compete freely against opposing viewpoints. When platforms, under regulatory pressure, implement content moderation, they are effectively acting as state agents, deciding which ideas are permissible. Age verification laws, for instance, are not about safety but about controlling access to information, which is a subtle form of gatekeeping that chills open discourse. Therefore, any intervention, whether by government mandate or platform compliance, distorts the necessary free exchange of thought.",
      "source": "target",
